    <string name="SectionOneTheoryDef_4">• Numerical expressions use only numbers and operation signs.\n
• Algebraic expressions use both numbers and letters joined by operations like +, −, ×, ÷, powers, or roots.\n
• Examples: a + b, x³ − y²/z, √2xy + 3x²y − 1.</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryDefQuestion_4">Is x² + 3x − 1 an algebraic expression? (True / False)</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryDefAnswerOne_4">True</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryDefAnswerTwo_4">False</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryDefAnswerThree_4">Neither</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryDefCorrectAnswer_4">True</string>

    <string name="SectionOneTheoryProperties_4">• Numerical expressions have sense only if all operations are possible (e.g., no division by zero).\n
• Algebraic expressions have a domain of definition — values that make all operations valid.\n
• The numerical value is found by replacing letters with numbers.\n
• Identities are true for all values (a + b ≡ b + a), while equations are true only for some (e.g., 3x + 1 = x + 1 ⇒ x = 1).</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryPropsQuestion_4">What is the value of 2x² − x + 3 for x = 2?</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryPropsAnswerOne_4">7</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryPropsAnswerTwo_4">9</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryPropsAnswerThree_4">13</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryPropsCorrectAnswer_4">9</string>

    <string name="SectionOneTheoryWorkedExamples_4">Find the domain of the expression 1/(x − 3).\n
Step 1: The expression is undefined when the denominator equals zero.\n
Step 2: x − 3 = 0 → x = 3.\n
Step 3: Domain: all real numbers except x = 3.</string>
    <string name="SectionOneTheoryWorkedExQuestion_4">For which value of x is 1/(x − 3) undefined?</string>
