    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryDef_4">• A ratio compares two numbers: a (antecedent) and b (consequent).\n
• Percent means "per hundred" and is written as %.\n
• Example: 80% = 80/100 = 0.8.</string>
    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryDefQuestion_4">What is 35% expressed as a fraction in lowest terms?</string>
    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryDefAnswerOne_4">35/10</string>
    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryDefAnswerTwo_4">7/20</string>
    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryDefAnswerThree_4">1/35</string>
    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryDefCorrectAnswer_4">7/20</string>

    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryProperties_4">• Ratios compare quantities of the same kind and don\'t depend on units.\n
• Some ratios (e.g., distance/time) define new quantities like speed.\n
• Percent formula: r = (a/b) × 100.\n
• Used in problems like discounts, yields, and population counts.</string>
    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryPropsQuestion_4">A class has 12 girls out of 30 students. What percentage are girls?</string>
    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryPropsAnswerOne_4">30%</string>
    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryPropsAnswerTwo_4">40%</string>
    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryPropsAnswerThree_4">50%</string>
    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryPropsCorrectAnswer_4">40%</string>

    <string name="SectionTwoTheoryWorkedExamples_4">A product costs 200 and is discounted by 15%. What is the final price?\n
Step 1: Calculate the discount: 15% of 200 = (15/100) × 200 = 30.\n
Step 2: Subtract from original: 200 − 30 = 170.\n
Step 3: Final price: 170.</string>
