    <string name="SectionFourTheoryDef_4">• A monomial is a product of numbers and letters (e.g., 3xy²).\n
• A polynomial is a sum of monomials (e.g., x² + 3x + 2).</string>
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryDefQuestion_4">What is the degree of the polynomial 4x³ − 2x + 7?</string>
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryDefAnswerOne_4">1</string>
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryDefAnswerTwo_4">2</string>
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryDefAnswerThree_4">3</string>
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryDefCorrectAnswer_4">3</string>


    <string name="SectionFourTheoryProperties_4">• In standard form, coefficients come first, followed by variables with powers.\n
• Polynomials can be monomials, binomials, or trinomials.\n
• The degree is the highest power of any term.\n
• Add/subtract by combining like terms; multiply each term with each other.</string>
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryPropsQuestion_4">What is (2x + 3) + (x − 1)?</string>
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryPropsAnswerOne_4">3x + 2</string>
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryPropsAnswerTwo_4">2x + 2</string>
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryPropsAnswerThree_4">3x − 2</string>
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryPropsCorrectAnswer_4">3x + 2</string>


    <string name="SectionFourTheoryWorkedExamples_4">Multiply (x + 2)(x + 3).\n
Step 1: Expand: x·x + x·3 + 2·x + 2·3.\n
Step 2: Simplify: x² + 3x + 2x + 6.\n
Step 3: Combine like terms: x² + 5x + 6.</string>
