    <string name="SectionSixTheoryDef_4">• A polynomial of degree n has the form P(x) = a₀xⁿ + a₁xⁿ⁻¹ + ... + aₙ.\n
• Terms are written in descending order of powers.</string>
    <string name="SectionSixTheoryDefQuestion_4">What is the leading coefficient of 5x⁴ − 3x² + 1?</string>
    <string name="SectionSixTheoryDefAnswerOne_4">1</string>
    <string name="SectionSixTheoryDefAnswerTwo_4">5</string>
    <string name="SectionSixTheoryDefAnswerThree_4">-3</string>
    <string name="SectionSixTheoryDefCorrectAnswer_4">5</string>


    <string name="SectionSixTheoryProperties_4">• Two polynomials are equal if all coefficients of matching powers are equal.\n
• Operations: add, subtract, multiply using arithmetic rules.\n
• Factorization rewrites a polynomial as a product (e.g., x² − a² = (x + a)(x − a)).\n
• Irreducible polynomials can\'t be factored (like primes).</string>
    <string name="SectionSixTheoryPropsQuestion_4">Which is the factored form of x² − 9?</string>
    <string name="SectionSixTheoryPropsAnswerOne_4">(x − 3)²</string>
    <string name="SectionSixTheoryPropsAnswerTwo_4">(x + 3)(x − 3)</string>
    <string name="SectionSixTheoryPropsAnswerThree_4">(x + 9)(x − 1)</string>
    <string name="SectionSixTheoryPropsCorrectAnswer_4">(x + 3)(x − 3)</string>

    <string name="SectionSixTheoryWorkedExamples_4">Factor x² + 5x + 6.\n
Step 1: Find two numbers that multiply to 6 and add to 5: 2 and 3.\n
Step 2: Write as (x + 2)(x + 3).\n
Step 3: Verify: (x + 2)(x + 3) = x² + 5x + 6. ✓</string>
    <string name="SectionSixTheoryWorkedExQuestion_4">What is the factored form of x² + 5x + 6?</string>
    <string name="SectionSixTheoryWorkedExAnswerOne_4">(x + 1)(x + 6)</string>
    <string name="SectionSixTheoryWorkedExAnswerTwo_4">(x + 2)(x + 4)</string>
    <string name="SectionSixTheoryWorkedExAnswerThree_4">(x + 2)(x + 3)</string>
    <string name="SectionSixTheoryWorkedExCorrectAnswer_4">(x + 2)(x + 3)</string>


