    <string name="SectionSevenTheoryDef_4">• Method of Undetermined Coefficients: assume a form, expand, and compare coefficients to find unknowns.\n
• Some polynomials can\'t be factorized; no general test exists.</string>
    <string name="SectionSevenTheoryDefQuestion_4">To factor x² + bx + c using undetermined coefficients, which condition must the two unknowns p and q satisfy?</string>
    <string name="SectionSevenTheoryDefAnswerOne_4">p + q = c and p · q = b</string>
    <string name="SectionSevenTheoryDefAnswerTwo_4">p · q = c and p + q = b</string>
    <string name="SectionSevenTheoryDefAnswerThree_4">p − q = b and p · q = c</string>
    <string name="SectionSevenTheoryDefCorrectAnswer_4">p · q = c and p + q = b</string>


    <string name="SectionSevenTheoryProperties_4">Key Facts about Polynomial Factorization:\n
• A polynomial of degree 1 is always irreducible (it has no factors of lower degree).\n
• A degree-2 polynomial is irreducible if its discriminant b² − 4ac &lt; 0.\n
• Every polynomial of degree ≥ 1 over the reals can be written as a product of degree-1 and irreducible degree-2 factors.\n
• The method of undetermined coefficients works by assuming a factored form and equating coefficients of each power.\n
• There is no universal algorithm to decide if a polynomial of degree ≥ 5 is factorizable.</string>
    <string name="SectionSevenTheoryPropsQuestion_4">Is x² + 1 factorable over the real numbers? (True / False)</string>
    <string name="SectionSevenTheoryPropsAnswerOne_4">True</string>
    <string name="SectionSevenTheoryPropsAnswerTwo_4">False</string>
    <string name="SectionSevenTheoryPropsAnswerThree_4">Neither</string>
    <string name="SectionSevenTheoryPropsCorrectAnswer_4">False</string>


    <string name="SectionSevenTheoryWorkedExamples_4">Factor x² − 5x + 6 using undetermined coefficients.\n
Step 1: Assume (x + p)(x + q) = x² + (p+q)x + pq.\n
Step 2: Match coefficients: p + q = −5, p · q = 6.\n
Step 3: Find p and q: −2 and −3 satisfy both conditions.\n
Step 4: Result: (x − 2)(x − 3).</string>
    <string name="SectionSevenTheoryWorkedExQuestion_4">What is the factored form of x² − 5x + 6?</string>
    <string name="SectionSevenTheoryWorkedExAnswerOne_4">(x − 1)(x − 6)</string>
    <string name="SectionSevenTheoryWorkedExAnswerTwo_4">(x + 2)(x + 3)</string>
    <string name="SectionSevenTheoryWorkedExAnswerThree_4">(x − 2)(x − 3)</string>
    <string name="SectionSevenTheoryWorkedExCorrectAnswer_4">(x − 2)(x − 3)</string>

